Oscar Wilde To Lord Alfred Douglas, 1897

Love letters between Oscar Wilde and Lord Alfred Douglas were eventually read out in the court case that saw Wilde serve two years for indecency and sodomy. 

This letter to his lover of six years was written just after Wilde was released from prison and had fled to France. Douglas, who was known as 'Bosie' to his friends, had a tempestuous relationship and would often argue and break up, but would always reconcile.

